### **Step-by-step breakdown of the command:**

```bash
$ cat wowfanfic.txt | perl -ne '@a = split(/\s/); foreach (@a) { print $_ . "\n"; }' | sort |  uniq -c | sort -n | tail -n 20
```

#### 1. **`cat wowfanfic.txt`**  
This reads the contents of the file `wowfanfic.txt` and outputs it to the next command in the pipeline.

#### 2. **`perl -ne '@a = split(/\s/); foreach (@a) { print $_ . "\n"; }'`**  
- `-n` tells Perl to loop over each line of input.
- `@a = split(/\s/)` splits each line into an array of words, using whitespace (spaces, tabs, newlines) as the delimiter.
- `foreach (@a) { print $_ . "\n"; }` prints each word on its own line.

**Result so far:** A list of all words from the file, each on its own line.

#### 3. **`sort`**  
Sorts all the words alphabetically.

#### 4. **`uniq -c`**  
Counts the number of times each word appears. It only keeps one copy of each word and prefixes the count.

**Example:**
```
3 the
2 and
1 wow
```

#### 5. **`sort -n`**  
Sorts the output numerically, based on the word count (from lowest to highest).

#### 6. **`tail -n 20`**  
Prints the last 20 lines of the output — i.e., the 20 most frequent words.

